                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d425">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.90H/32: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Straus</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-06T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 6, 1935—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>209. Your No. 464, June 4, 11 a.m. The Department’s policy is to conclude
                    commercial agreements providing that most-favored-nation treatment shall be
                    extended unconditionally, without compensation and without request. It does not
                    appear that the Afghan Government differs in principle from this proposal. The
                    Afghan counterproposal is ambiguous and consequently the Department much prefers
                    its own draft of Article IV.</p>
                <p>Your position with respect to languages of final text approved.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
